Koninkrijk","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England"},"en":{"1204–":"1204–Deceased","1205–1242":"1205–1242","1225–1281":"1225–1281","1234–1282":"1234–1282","1239–1290":"1239–1290","1243–Female":"1243–Deceased","1204–Female":"1204–Deceased","1239":"1239","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1225":"1225","about 1239":"about 1239","1234":"1234","1243":"1243","1242":"1242","about 1234":"about 1234","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Ellesmere, Shropshire, England":"Ellesmere, Shropshire, England","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Markham Clinton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eiville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Cecile, Fernand, Laurent, Marcel, Normand, Roch, Yvon.","Swiss French: variant of <b>Miéville</b>, topographic name for someone who lived in the middle of the village, from French <i>(en) mi ville</i>, Latin <i>mediavilla</i>, or a habitational name from Miéville, a place in Switzerland. Compare   Mainville   and   Mayville  .","History: Pierre Miville <i>dit</i> Le Suisse from Fribourg in Switzerland married Charlotte Maugis in France <i>c.</i> 1631, died in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Ma(i)nville</i> and <i>Mayville</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Mainville","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Colette, Emile, Lucien, Normand, Rodolphe.","Altered form of Swiss French   Miville  . Compare   Manville   2 and   Mayville  .","In some cases possibly also French: habitational name from any of several places so called, in Aisne, Essonne, Loiret, and Moselle. Compare   Manville   3."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Robert de Eiville was born in 1204, in Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Robert Daiville. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"